iew/pr-22/sv/arbeten/g%C3%B6teborgsaffisch/gbg_poster08_hu_d3060a15d014ff98.webp 2x&#xA;            &#34;&#xA;            sizes=&#34;100vw&#34;&#xA;          /&gt;&#xA;          &lt;img&#xA;            alt=&#34;Header example&#34;&#xA;            title=&#34;Header example&#34;&#xA;            src=&#34;../../../preview/pr-22/sv/arbeten/g%C3%B6teborgsaffisch/gbg_poster08_hu_5c2dbd270b0d2541.jpg&#34;&#xA;            height=&#34;1280&#34;&#xA;            width=&#34;1920&#34;&#xA;            class=&#34;img-fluid&#34;&#xA;            loading=&#34;lazy&#34;&#xA;          /&gt;&#xA;        &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/figure&gt;&lt;h2&gt;Introduction&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This tutorial will show you how to create a simple theme in Hugo. I assume that you are familiar with HTML, the bash command line, and that you are comfortable using Markdown to format content. I&amp;rsquo;ll explain how Hugo uses templates and how you can organize your templates to create a theme. I won&amp;rsquo;t cover using CSS to style your theme.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
